    <article id="Lec32">
        <header class="html-article-header">
            <h2><span class="html-lec-heading">Lecture 32: What is HTML 5?</span></h2>
        </header>
        <p class="sec-para-main">HTML is set of rules which defines how an element would look like, you can see the
            standard at <a href="https://html.spec.whatwg.org/">HTML spec</a>.Specs is followed by every browser and
            implemented
            accordingly. HTML 5 defines the new version of the HTML standard that contains new attributes, elements
            and
            other things like 2d/3d animation which aren't exactly HTML but helps to build a better webpage.You
            can't go
            back to a previous HTML version, even if you define a document type as HTML4 or older but put an HTML5
            element inside it, then it will still be implemented by the browser. </p>
    </article>
    <article id="Lec33">
        <header class="html-article-header">
            <h2><span class="html-lec-heading">Lecture 33: Block vs Inline elements - Divs and Spans</span></h2>
        </header>
        <p class="sec-para-main"><span class="keyword">Inline elements</span> does not break the document flow and
            just takes the space
            required by the content inside
            it,
            any content placed after it will be placed right next to it.
            <span class="keyword">Block level elements</span> break the document flow and take the whole space for
            themselves, any element placed
            after block level element will be placed in the next line.
            <span class="keyword">Divs</span> acts like a container of the content and helps to wrap things up
            together which you may want to
            style
            differently than rest of the document, it is a block level element hence any element placed after div
            will
            start in a new line. <span class="keyword">Span</span> also works similarly like div the only
            difference is that it is a inline level element and hence doesn't break the document flow.
        </p>
    </article>
    <article id="Lec34">
        <header class="html-article-header">
            <h2><span class="html-lec-heading">Lecture 34: HR,BR,sub and sup</span></h2>
        </header>
        <p class="sec-para-main"><code class="html-tags">&lthr></code> stands for horizontal rule basically it puts
            a horizontal line
            through
            the document. <code class="html-tags">&ltbr></code> stands for break which breaks the document flow and
            anything which comes after it starts from a new line.<code class="html-tags">&ltsub></code> is useful if
            you
            want to place an element below the baseline(line where all other elements are placed).<code
                class="html-tags">&ltsup></code> places the element above the baseline.
            Proper use of <code class="html-tags">&ltbr></code> can be read on <a
                href="https://html.spec.whatwg.org/multipage/text-level-semantics.html#the-br-element">HTMLspec</a>
        </p>
    </article>
